<h1>Example 1</h1>

<section>
	<p class="example-intro">Commas are essential building blocks of complex and compound sentences. One of the most common uses of a comma is to join two independent clauses with a coordinating conjunction. Coordinating conjunctions include: and, but, for, or, nor, yet, and so. Commas are not needed when a sentence has one subject with multiple predicates. </p>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The system was designed to track data between patients with similar health histories and similar treatment plans <span class="red">and</span> it had provided a wealth of knowledge to the hospital's research team.</h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">In this example we see two independent clauses joined with the coordinating conjunction, and. In order to keep this from being a run-on, which is what it is right now, we'll need to add a comma before the coordinating conjunction.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The system was designed to track data between patients with similar health histories and similar treatment plans<span class="green">, and</span> it had provided a wealth of knowledge to the hospital's research team.</h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">By adding the comma before the coordinating conjunction, and, we form a grammatically correct compound sentence.</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">Nurses need to be attentive to the patient's spoken and unspoken needs<span class="red">, and</span> do their best to provide for those needs.</h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This sentence is an example of a single subject with multiple predicates. In this case the subject is "nurses," and the predicates are "need to be attentive to the patient's spoken and unspoken needs and "do their best to provide for those needs." In situations like this, commas are not needed between the predicates.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">Nurses need to be attentive to the patient's spoken and unspoken needs<span class="green"> and</span> do their best to provide for those needs.</h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">To correct the sentence, all we need to do is remove the unnecessary comma.</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

