<h1>Example 3</h1>

<section>
	<p class="example-intro">Commas can be needed when a sentence includes and introductory phrase, a dependent clause, or a non-essential clause. The following examples will review the proper ways to use commas in these situations.</p>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">After checking the patient's vitals <span class="red">the</span> nurse took a blood sample.</h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">Our first example shows us a sentence with the introductory phrase, "After checking the patient's vitals." In order to make this sentence correct, we need to add a comma after the introductory phrase.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">After checking the patient's vitals<span class="green">, </span>the nurse took a blood sample.</h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">Adding the comma after our introductory phrase corrects the sentence. Introductory phrases set up or provide context for the rest of the sentence.</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">To ensure that they provide quality care<span class="red"> healthcare providers</span> must always stay up to date with clinical research.</h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This sentence provides an example of a dependent clause. The clause "to ensure that they provide quality care" depends upon the rest of the sentence for its context, and because of this, it needs to be followed by a comma.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">To ensure that they provide quality care<span class="green">,</span> healthcare providers must always stay up to date with clinical research.</h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">The sentence is corrected by providing the missing comma after our dependent clauses. Remember, dependent clauses are those that don't form complete thoughts on their own.</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The patient's primary physician requested a blood gas analysis<span class="red"> which</span> includes pH, pO<sub>2</sub>, and hemoglobin.</h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">Here we see an example of an non-essential clause. The clause, "which includes pH, pO<sub>2</sub>, and hemoglobin," is not an essential part of the sentence, as the sentence still provides the same meaning whether this clause is included or not. Commas should be used in these situations.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The patient's primary physician requested a blood gas analysis<span class="green">, which</span> includes pH, pO<sub>2</sub>, and hemoglobin.</h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">The sentence is corrected by adding the necessary comma before the non-essential clause, "which includes pH, pO<sub>2</sub>, and hemoglobin."</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

