<h1>Example 4</h1>

<section>
	<p class="example-intro">Commas also need to be used in situations with lists that contain more than two items. This comma is known as the "Oxford comma." Some style guides say it isn't strictly necessary, but the APA recommends always using it to improve sentence clarity.</p>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">During the initial examination, the nurse recorded the patients height, weight<span class="red"> and</span> blood pressure.</h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">In this example, we are given a list of three items. The last two items are joined with the coordinating conjunction, "and," alone. This can be a confusing structure because weight and blood pressure could be interpreted as a joint second item in the list, when in fact the three items are intended to be distinct and equal weighted.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">During the initial examination, the nurse recorded the patients height, weight<span class="green">, and</span> blood pressure.</h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">Adding the Oxford comma gives the list the balance it was missing with its initial structure, and the sentence is corrected.</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>


